<DOC><DOCNO> AP881102-0192 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-02-88 2107EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     11-02 0318</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Sudan,0330</SECOND><HEAD>Police Disperse Rioters</HEAD><BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police on Wednesday used tear gas andbatons to disperse thousands of rioting young people who shouted``No sugar, no bread!'' and ``Down with the dictators,'' witnessessaid.   It was the fifth straight day of protests against high foodprices and the government of Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi. Officialsreported several arrests but no casualties.   Khartoum Commissioner Fatih Abdoun told the protesters thegovernment would do its best to ease shortages of bread and sugar.   Moslem fundamentalists and university students joined thedemonstrations, which ended by mid-afternoon. Many protesters had towalk home under a burning sun because the disturbances shut downpublic bus service.   The city center was almost deserted, except for riot police whocontinued to patrol streets littered with ashes from burned tires.   High school students began protesting last Saturday, throwingstones and burning tires in the streets of Khartoum and Omdurman,the capital's twin city across the Nile River.   On Tuesday, riot police fired into the air to disperse youths whoattacked several government installations, including Khartoum's mainlocal government building and the Cabinet offices.   The newspaper Al-Sudani reported that shots also were firedTuesday to disperse stone-throwers at the U.S. Embassy. Riot policeon Wednesday sealed off roads leading to the embassy and variousgovernment ministries.   Schools and universities have not been closed officially, butmany were shuttered out of fear that demonstrators would attackstudents who were not participating.   In 1985, 10 days of riots against high food prices led to ageneral strike that ended the 16-year dictatorship of formerPresident Gaafar Nimeiri. Those protests were led by professionalsand unionists, however, and the current disturbances appear to haveinvolved only young people.   Mahdi was elected prime minister in 1986. His government facessevere economic problems, including an $11-billion foreign debt and70 percent inflation.</TEXT></DOC>